Item categories have an interesting bit about them that may seem broken, but is easily avoidable. 
Items may not be assigned to a specific creative category without a special component, **in tandem**. *Some* of them will work, but others will begin to go into other categories after a certain amount registered.

To lock them to one category, using the `"category"` description property, one must also use the `creative_category` component to avoid overflow. These should "match".

Example:
```json
{
    "format_version": "1.16.100",
    "minecraft:item": {
        "description": {
            "identifier": "yanasakana:kyanite_axe",
            "category": "Equipment" 
        },
        "components": {
            "minecraft:creative_category": {
                "parent": "itemGroup.name.axe" // Matches Equipment, because it is in that tab
            },
             ...
        },
        "events": { ... }
    }
}
```

If you are wanting to use the new `/execute` syntax but are receiving errors such as "Unexpected '@e' in 'execute as >>@e<<", then make sure your manifest's "min_engine_version" is at least 1.19.50.
```json
{
  "format_version": 2,
  "header": {
    "name": "pack.name",
    "description": "pack.description",
    "uuid": "01234567-89ab-cdef-0123-456789abcdef",
    "min_engine_version": [1, 19, 50],
    "version": [1, 0, 0]
  }
}
```

`warning:` This method requires `experimental` toggles turned on.

You can place `run_command` into any entity *event* to play slash commands and Molang, similar to Animation Controllers. This goes alongside any `add` and `remove` keys. Please notice the lack of `/` in the command.

```json
{
  "add": {
    "component_groups": [
      "fc:normal_player"
    ]
  },
  "run_command": {
    "command": [
      "give @a stick"
    ]
  }
}
```

